Supply Chain Optimization Python MILP Model

Otto-von-Guericke-Universitt Magdeburg | Master's Project

Linear programming model for multi-stage supply chain cost optimization

Reduced
Total Cost
Increased
Utilization

Challenge

Academic research project addressing multi-stage supply chain optimization from quarries to plants to customers, with complex cost structures and capacity constraints.

Strategy

Developed Python-based mixed integer linear programming model using PuLP library to minimize total supply chain costs while satisfying demand and capacity constraints across all stages.

Execution

  • Modeled supply chain network with 5 quarries, 12 plants, and 72 customer locations
  • Implemented MILP optimization using PuLP with transportation and production constraints
  • Created Sankey diagrams visualizing optimal material flow patterns
  • Built Excel dashboards comparing optimized vs. baseline cost scenarios

Impact

Achieved reduction in total supply chain costs and improvement in plant utilization. The model demonstrated significant potential for real-world industrial applications.

GA-Based Staff Scheduling Optimization

Otto-von-Guericke-Universitt Magdeburg | Seminar Thesis

AI-driven workforce optimization using evolutionary algorithms

Grew
Schedule Efficiency
Dropped
Planning Time

Challenge

Traditional staff scheduling methods struggled with complex constraints including skill requirements, shift preferences, labor regulations, and demand variability.

Strategy

Developed genetic algorithm-based optimization system that evolves scheduling solutions through selection, crossover, and mutation operations to find near-optimal staff assignments.

Execution

  • Implemented GA workflow: Population Selection Crossover Mutation Evaluation
  • Designed fitness function balancing cost, coverage, and employee satisfaction
  • Created comparison analysis: GA vs. traditional manual scheduling methods
  • Visualized convergence with fitness curve charts across 500+ generations

Impact

Achieved improvement in schedule efficiency and reduced planning time. The GA approach consistently outperformed traditional methods in handling complex constraint scenarios.
